Continuing individual. I got much better views today than yesterday, as the bird was foraging remarkably close to Upper Bay Rd. Adding to my rather basic comments from yesterday (a large, lanky bird, with long legs and a thin, long neck; generally gray overall with some brown on the coverts), today, I was able to view a lot of fine plumage details, especially on the head and neck. This bird has thin, orange eye-rings, and its irises appear to be a dark orangish color. It also has a rusty orange crown, which is a distinctly different color from the pinkish red on the loral area and forehead. I also noticed fairly extensive white mottling along the sides of the head and neck. This bird did not appear to be bothered by my presence at all, occasionally passing within 6-7 feet of me. It did seem to be concerned by the ravens and turkey vultures that would pass overhead, glancing up when they flew by. Of note, I also watched it inflate its throat a few times, giving a croak sound while doing so. Not sure what that means. Super glad I made the 2nd trip to see it again.

It was very rewarding to see it so close;  I could see it close its eyes from time to time,  preen, stretch, and eat. *Rare. I was wrapping up my walk and had already put my gear away, but was chatting with a friend who I'd run into in the parking lot. A PIWO flew over noisily which made me look towards the northeast. I noticed a flock of large birds flying lazily, heading our way. I fully expected them to be CAGO, but jokingly said "Watch those be Sandhill Cranes." As I finished that sentence and the birds approached, I realized that they were indeed Sandhill Cranes and scrambled to grab my camera out of my car and snap a doc shot. The birds flew directly over us heading southwest, and kept going until they were out of sight. Interestingly, the birds never made a peep as they flew by.

Continuing individual. I got much better views today than yesterday, as the bird was foraging remarkably close to Upper Bay Rd. Adding to my rather basic comments from yesterday (a large, lanky bird, with long legs and a thin, long neck; generally gray overall with some brown on the coverts), today, I was able to view a lot of fine plumage details, especially on the head and neck. This bird has thin, orange eye-rings, and its irises appear to be a dark orangish color. It also has a rusty orange crown, which is a distinctly different color from the pinkish red on the loral area and forehead. I also noticed fairly extensive white mottling along the sides of the head and neck. This bird did not appear to be bothered by my presence at all, occasionally passing within 6-7 feet of me. It did seem to be concerned by the ravens and turkey vultures that would pass overhead, glancing up when they flew by. Of note, I also watched it inflate its throat a few times, giving a croak sound while doing so. Not sure what that means. Super glad I made the 2nd trip to see it again.

When I arrived at 10 a.m., two adults and two colts were feeding in a field. Shortly thereafter they flew to a spit in the wetlands to preen, stretch, and "dance" together. I was about 40-50 yards from the cranes and used a 600 mm lens.

Video and audio taken of this flock as it circled in a spiral 100m directly over my house. Continuing individual. I got much better views today than yesterday, as the bird was foraging remarkably close to Upper Bay Rd. Adding to my rather basic comments from yesterday (a large, lanky bird, with long legs and a thin, long neck; generally gray overall with some brown on the coverts), today, I was able to view a lot of fine plumage details, especially on the head and neck. This bird has thin, orange eye-rings, and its irises appear to be a dark orangish color. It also has a rusty orange crown, which is a distinctly different color from the pinkish red on the loral area and forehead. I also noticed fairly extensive white mottling along the sides of the head and neck. This bird did not appear to be bothered by my presence at all, occasionally passing within 6-7 feet of me. It did seem to be concerned by the ravens and turkey vultures that would pass overhead, glancing up when they flew by. Of note, I also watched it inflate its throat a few times, giving a croak sound while doing so. Not sure what that means. Super glad I made the 2nd trip to see it again.

(continuing) Four sandhill cranes — two adults and two colts — flew overhead just as we got to the trail beside the main pond, and landed in a field to feed. They flew to the pond at 10:25 a.m. I saw several displays that seemed playful (adult to colt) or competitive (colt to colt). At one point, about an hour later, one of the colts was vocalizing quite a bit and then suddenly flew off (video available). It circled around the pond but returned when its sibling and parents stayed put. Shortly thereafter they all flew to a field to feed.

Fotos.

When I arrived at 10 a.m., two adults and two colts were feeding in a field. Shortly thereafter they flew to a spit in the wetlands to preen, stretch, and "dance" together. The adult postures included bowing and leaping, which the two colts obviously mimicked. They were surrounded by dozens of canada geese and other waterfowl, including six snow geese. I was about 40-50 yards from the cranes and used a 600 mm lens.

Pair flew in low from north, calling loudly, and landed among grazing geese on north side of cemetery. Fed in lawn among gravestones, then walked to far NE corner at Lexington and continued feeding in lawn. Approached to within 20 m (measured) as I sat in car, and fed for 15 min that close, showing no fear as I took photos. After they walked away, I checked ground where they were feeding but found only goose droppings.  They fed extensively in a small area on what appeared to be corn kernels, so perhaps they consumed all of it. In the past some visitors have scattered corn and birdseed in cemetery for wildlife and that may have been the case here.

Locality: Pine Chapel, Moss, and Hunts Gin Rds.
IRWD San Joaquin Marsh & Wildlife Sanctuary, Irvine
Observation Details: Found by Susan Kaveggia and Star Howard at 12:30 PM when the bird flew in and landed on the island in Pond 2. This was a long-legged, long-necked bird, with a moderate length spear or dagger-like bill. The plumage was mostly gray, but with extensive rusty coloration in the upper wing coverts and scapulars, blackish outer primaries, a rusty or brownish crown and nape, and pinkish wash to the forehead. In comparison with a Great Egret, it stood about equally tall, but had slightly longer legs and a shorter neck, and the body was noticeably bulkier, appearing about twice as massive as the egret. During observation it vocalized several times, giving a short grebe-like call. It flew off at 3:30 PM, high and to the east and it did not seem likely that it was going to return.

Observation Details: Five cranes, all in adult plumage, unexpectedly found in large field near a marsh. Judging by size, two appeared to be males, three females. One presumed male was calling frequently. Considering successful nesting/fledging of two offspring in the general area in 2019 (unknown until recently), 2021, and 2022, we speculated about the origin of these birds and whether they may have born in somewhere in this southeast-Quabbin region. It takes 2-3 years for immature birds to acquire adult plumage. These are not any of the two adults with recently fledged young reported more than 2 weeks ago. Photos.

Continuing individual. I got much better views today than yesterday, as the bird was foraging remarkably close to Upper Bay Rd. Adding to my rather basic comments from yesterday (a large, lanky bird, with long legs and a thin, long neck; generally gray overall with some brown on the coverts), today, I was able to view a lot of fine plumage details, especially on the head and neck. This bird has thin, orange eye-rings, and its irises appear to be a dark orangish color. It also has a rusty orange crown, which is a distinctly different color from the pinkish red on the loral area and forehead. I also noticed fairly extensive white mottling along the sides of the head and neck. This bird did not appear to be bothered by my presence at all, occasionally passing within 6-7 feet of me. It did seem to be concerned by the ravens and turkey vultures that would pass overhead, glancing up when they flew by. Of note, I also watched it inflate its throat a few times, giving a croak sound while doing so. Not sure what that means. Super glad I made the 2nd trip to see it again.

(continuing) Four sandhill cranes — two adults and two colts — flew overhead just as we got to the trail beside the main pond, and landed in a field to feed. They flew to the pond at 10:25 a.m. I saw several displays that seemed playful (adult to colt) or competitive (colt to colt). At one point, about an hour later, one of the colts was vocalizing quite a bit and then suddenly flew off (video available). It circled around the pond but returned when its sibling and parents stayed put. Shortly thereafter they all flew to a field to feed.

(continuing) Four sandhill cranes — two adults and two colts — flew overhead just as we got to the trail beside the main pond, and landed in a field to feed. They flew to the pond at 10:25 a.m. I saw several displays that seemed playful (adult to colt) or competitive (colt to colt). At one point, about an hour later, one of the colts was vocalizing quite a bit and then suddenly flew off (video available). It circled around the pond but returned when its sibling and parents stayed put. Shortly thereafter they all flew to a field to feed.

When I arrived at 10 a.m., two adults and two colts were feeding in a field. Shortly thereafter they flew to a spit in the wetlands to preen, stretch, and "dance" together. The adult postures included bowing and leaping, which the two colts obviously mimicked. They were surrounded by dozens of canada geese and other waterfowl, including six snow geese. I was about 40-50 yards from the cranes and used a 600 mm lens.

Pair flew in low from north, calling loudly, and landed among grazing geese on north side of cemetery. Fed in lawn among gravestones, then walked to far NE corner at Lexington and continued feeding in lawn. Approached to within 20 m (measured) as I sat in car, and fed for 15 min that close, showing no fear as I took photos. After they walked away, I checked ground where they were feeding but found only goose droppings.  They fed extensively in a small area on what appeared to be corn kernels, so perhaps they consumed all of it. In the past some visitors have scattered corn and birdseed in cemetery for wildlife and that may have been the case here.

**rare; continuing HY first found two weeks ago by Jonathan Eckerson and Evan Lipton; not present in fields earlier at 8:15 but present upon my return at 8:55; many photos clearly establish species, but subspecies ID more subtle, though ID of 'Lesser' Sandhill by structure is more obvious than ID of Lesser Yellowlegs by structure; short legs, with very short exposed tibia about 1/2 (or less) length tibiotarsus, short bill about length of head, and overall body size no larger than large Canada Goose; when neck extended, probably about 3 ft tall; hatch-year bird wit feathered crown and extensive reddish brown wash on top of head and nape as well as media and lesser coverts and scapulars; also distinctive of cabadebsisw is reduced red cap, which is apparent even on juveniles as a darker area is visible in good light on forehead that extends to just behind eye and when viewed head on (when feeding) it extends only to mid-crown and has a strong, shallow, rounded notch at center (as on adults) in contrast to the much longer red cap extending behind eye on tabida and rowani; seen very near (and on) gravel road through field behind red barn where Xmas trees are being sold; my first for Bristol Co. and first canadensis in the state, though I have seen one each in Maine and Rhode Island

By far the most I've ever seen here, generally I do good to find a handful somewhere on my (very) infrequent visits. First cranes were along Hwy 89, in a field along Howard Moore Rd. This group had 125, with 3's and 4's dropping in regularly. Saw more in flight to the north, so drove up Howard Moore. The big group was about 1/2 mile up Howard Moore in a big field to the west of the road. There were a minimum of 600 birds here, with some I know I couldn't see behind a rise because I saw birds coming in and disappearing. Nearby had 2 other groups of 150-200, 75 and numerous smaller family groups and birds flying here and there.

A single, much smaller crane than the Greater Sandhills it was with, approximately 1/2 the bulk of the others. At all times it showed darker remiges, a much smaller bill (perhaps 1/2 the length of the birds it was with, and much skinnier), and much shorter legs (approx, 1/2 the length of all surrounding birds, with a much shorter (and proportionately shorter) leg projection beyond the tail. Its neck was noticeably shorter than those of the others. And a less extensive white cheek patch would presume a runt Greater would not show the darker remiges, smalwr cheek patch, and differing proportions, but am happy to be corrected if this is wrong. Photographed at multiple angles, this combination of traits was consistent throughout the observation. Full details to be submitted to MBRC.

Media notes: Rattle calls. Likely a male, assuming the female was the one on the nest. Normalized to -3 using Audacity.
Observation Details: This crane landed and walked around the area for over an hour until the human had to leave. At one point it wandered towards an area that had a nest in the past and another crane rose and squawked a command to keep moving. Likely the walker was a male with the female telling him to go get the groceries. A short while later he called his lament and began searching for the groceries. Therefore a nest is suspected again, though currently unable to be viewed and will be even more difficult once the greenery develops.

Pair flew in low from north, calling loudly, and landed among grazing geese on north side of cemetery. Fed in lawn among gravestones, then walked to far NE corner at Lexington and continued feeding in lawn. Approached to within 20 m (measured) as I sat in car, and fed for 15 min that close, showing no fear as I took photos. After they walked away, I checked ground where they were feeding but found only goose droppings.  They fed extensively in a small area on what appeared to be corn kernels, so perhaps they consumed all of it. In the past some visitors have scattered corn and birdseed in cemetery for wildlife and that may have been the case here.

All seen on the ground in the survey area with most (4700) on the east side of 600E near the marsh/pond and ditch.  Large flocks previously seen to the south were seen heading to this resting/roosting area. Hardly any (400) seen on the north side of 1000S today and none on the east side of 500E or out in the open in the ag land north and south of 1100S.  This weeks worth of highly documented surveys should convince you that the filter needs to be changed for LaPorte Co, as has repeatedly been suggested at the bottom of the last paragragh; Change the filter to 20,000 as it is for Starke Co, which is less than two (2) miles to the south. Jackson and Green Counties also have 20,000 as the filter cutoff. , and Starke County. LaPorte County is an adjacent county to Jasper-Pulaski and the SACR are only going to continue increasing.   Although this count of 7,360 is just an on-ground count with no dusk flight count the SACR on ground numbers dropped in the past two daily readings from the on-ground high of 13,900 on 11.29.17 and also from 12,480 on 12.04.17, just four (4) days ago. Excluding the first count the mean on-ground count from 11.29.17 through 12.06.17 was 11,081. The drop in the on-ground count is associated with the drop in the temperature, as would be expected. The temperature dropped down to 13.5 F at 0515 at the LaPorte Municipal Airport, and down to 12.6 F at Kingsford Heights  this AM. Although in speaking with the man that plows the local roads some do remain around during the winter as he stated that they would be out in the road when he was plowing.   Surveyed this area intensively for @ one week. Had 10,400 on 11.26.17; 14,900 on 11.29; and 17,350 on 12.01; 15,605 on 12.02.17; 16,803 on 12.03.17; 17,080 on 12.04.17, 11,100 on 12.06.17; and 7,360 on 12.08.17 ( which did not include the dusk flight count.). Fairly consistent counts until the cold weather hit.  Believe numbers dropped the last two days due to the colder weather causing migration.  17,000 previously reported for LaPorte Co in March of 2015 http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S22388042 without any supporting documentation   and the SACR population is experiencing an increase. Not this many were here two (2) years ago. Many other local checklists by several observers from earlier this year showing 5,000-8,000 SACR @ 5 miles to the SW of this roosting location. It is 23 miles to Jasper-Pulaski.  This observation was continued until dusk to include the SACR flying in to roost as observer had knowledge and experience of seeing large flocks nearby earlier this year. There are no other dusk checklists that have been done at this location. This roost is a northern roost that the cranes foraging nearby use rather than flying the 23 miles to Jasper -Pulaski.  Same as gulls use local lakes as roosting locations rather than returning to Lake Michigan after foraging at landfills. One checklist done earlier this year, by this observer, noted that 5,000 cranes were heading to the 600E area. http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S34610409  Another checklist which the observer did found 3,000 SACR flying in a southerly direction to the north of the checklist location  http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S27937963. There are many cranes here.  Three (3) individuals that the observer sppoke with during the week noted they thought there were more cranes here than at Jasper-Pulaski. If you look at a map the area available to them is larger at this location. Recommend changing the filter to 20,000 as it is for Jackson and Green Counties. LaPorte County is an adjacent county to Jasper-Pulaski and the SACR are only going to continue increasing.

Media notes: Photo by Alan Rawle.
Observation Details: Five cranes, all in adult plumage, unexpectedly found in large field near a marsh. Judging by size, two appeared to be males, three females. One presumed male was calling frequently. Considering successful nesting/fledging of two offspring in the general area in 2019 (unknown until recently), 2021, and 2022, we speculated about the origin of these birds and whether they may have born in somewhere in this southeast-Quabbin region. It takes 2-3 years for immature birds to acquire adult plumage. These are not any of the two adults with recently fledged young reported more than 2 weeks ago. Photos.

When I arrived at 10 a.m., two adults and two colts were feeding in a field. Shortly thereafter they flew to a spit in the wetlands to preen, stretch, and "dance" together. The adult postures included bowing and leaping, which the two colts obviously mimicked. They were surrounded by dozens of canada geese and other waterfowl, including six snow geese. I was about 40-50 yards from the cranes and used a 600 mm lens.

Observation Details: Family of four, Florida Sandhill Cranes; one adult male (injured one week ago), one adult female, two seemingly healthy chicks aged approximately 7 weeks (rechecked my notes, they hatched on/about February 28-29, 2020)

Media notes: This, one of two chicks in this "lakeside" sandhill crane family, begins to stand after resting on the ground for about 3-4 minutes-- rising to follow its family members leaving the immediate area where they were enjoying seed eating under a hanging bird feeder. Both Sandhill Crane chicks' down feathers now (the chick seen here is about one-month of age) are beginning to be replaced with new plumage... seen well here in this photograph.
Observation Details: Photographs hereunder are of the "lakeside" sandhill crane family, 2 adults with two immature chicks - - these chicks now about one month of age; the same family as seen and reported to e-bird (with photographs) in the last few days (early April 2020).  As well, sighted today - - was another sandhill crane family, approx. 1/8 mile north of the "lakeside" family, across the main road (SR 674), just above Lake Wimauma... this family of four included one adult male, one adult female and 2 chicks appearing to be no more than 7 days of age. This family was foraging in an oak-tree shaded area, an open and quiet area, part of a large church property.
Foraging just north of boardwalk gazebo.

Media notes: Photo by Alan Rawle.
Observation Details: Continuing family group. The birds were in the habit, up until last time we saw them, of moving on foot from their preferred daytime foraging area to their late-afternoon/evening spot. We expected to once again see them change location this way, but instead the birds took flight from the higher area and maneuvered through the air to get to the grassy edge of the large pond and marsh. There were many contact calls going on, most likely because one of the young birds flew off-course and didn't re-join the other three for a couple of minutes. Instead of joining the family on the grass, the independent colt flew  straight into the marsh where the foursome generally feeds until sunset. The others followed it in. The colts are flying about a week earlier than last year's offspring.
Continuing beyond friendly bird. Managed to cross the road on our way out.

12.18.17 Change the filter to 20,000 as it is for Starke Co, which is less than two (2) miles to the south. Jackson and Green Counties also have 20,000 as the filter cutoff. , and Starke County. LaPorte County is an adjacent county to Jasper-Pulaski and the SACR are only going to continue increasing.   12.14.17  Still no action on this checklist or these http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S40832917   and http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S40852067.  10700 previously approved for a 11.26.17 checklist at this same location.  17000 previously approved at location @ eight (8) miles to the SW in 2015  http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S22388042 with no supporting documentation and SACR numbers are increasing.  Filter should be set to 20,000 as in Jackson and Greene Counties.  Surveyed this area intensively for @ one week. Had 10,400 on 11.26.17; 14,900 on 11.29; and 17,350 on 12.01; 15,605 on 12.02.17; 16,803 on 12.03.17; 17,080 on 12.04.17, 11,100 on 12.06.17; and 7,360 on 12.08.17 ( which did not include the dusk flight count.). Fairly consistent counts until the cold weather hit.  Believe numbers dropped the last two days due to the colder weather causing migration.    FHC Counted cranes on the ground and those coming from @ 417 PM - 450 PM.   10,980 on the ground  + 6,370 in flight = 17,350 cranes  S 600E in field on east side south of pond- 2600 birds @ 1440 PM Upon looking these did not take flight en masse to move to the roosting area immediately to the north before 445 PM. The area they were thickest in was immediately to the south of it.  There were an additional 700 birds seen on the east side of S 600E, north of the east pond at 445 PM however.  E 1125S, east of S 600E  -  1060 birds @ 1510 PM 1030 on the south side and 30 on the north Didn't check it at dusk.  E 1100N, west of S 600E, near the low spot - 1320 birds @ 1535 PM Not as many as there were two (2) days ago.  E 1000S, north side, west of S 550E - 5,000 birds @ 1600 PM There were none on the east half of this field as there had been two (2) days ago. These were counted by scope and many were missed due to some being out of sight in low spots and behind vegetation from the best viewing location. Since only about half of the surface area previously covered by the birds two days ago was now covered that estimate of 7,000 birds was most likely low.  This flock took off all at the same time while I was there starting with the birds at the far west end and flew across the road and settled on the east side of S 500E which was the typical staging area that I recall from the past. None settled in the marsh on the south side of E 1000S, but all settled on the ag land on the west side of it.  S 500E, east side, south of E 1000S - 1000 birds @ 1550 PM  S 550E, east side low spot - zero (0) birds at 215 PM CST and didn't see any there just after dusk. Some were seen settling there at @ 445 PM CST but it was too dark to count. These birds were coming from the north.  Birds Flying in from 1615 PM to 1650 PM  - 6,370 birds 4,070 + 2300  Sat on S 500E and counted birds periodically, about every three minutes, as they came in. From 417 PM to 434 PM I had a total of 2,440 birds in 6 counts spaced 3 minutes apart. Birds seen in flight were 300, 600, 220, 600, 190, and 530. Averaging the total birds by the six counts gives 407 birds per minute. Multiplying this rate by the time watched of 20 minutes gives total birds of 8,140. To get amount to use I divided that amount in half, giving 4,070 cranes, which would subtract any of the birds previously seen on the ground to the south (1,060 + 1,320 = 2,380 birds) plus an additional 1,690 birds to avoid overcounting.  More birds continued to come in after 437 PM until the time I left, with more coming in yet. Had @ 125 birds minute by averaging. Time would be 23 minutes from 437-500PM and used 100 birds per min for 2300 birds. Cranes were still coming in from the north when I left.

Media notes: Sandhill Crane
Observation Details: We were barely past the Border Patrol buildings when we began to hear Sandhills in the distance.  The air almost vibrated with the sound at times.  No effort was made to seriously judge how many cranes were there, but at least 2000 wouldn't be unrealistic.  The birds were coming & going continuously, with large concentrations settling into areas W and SW of the golf course.  We had great looks at the birds from the brush dump near the western end of Fairway Ln.  This is the lane that turns right just past the stucco golf course 'gate' when heading to the lake.  Just before the lake, there are two golf course ponds off to the right.  A small observation platform and parking area are by a short, narrow sandy lane that runs between these ponds and ponds on the opposite side of the lane.  Masses of cranes were seen across the latter.  //  A coyote was standing at the edge of the golf greens.

Observation Details: When we saw so many flying up then landing again, we hurried over from the golf course to Cochise Lake. When we arrived, there was a girl that was trying to walk out into the flock and scaring them. I yelled at her three times before she went back to her car. At the car, what may have been her father, was operating a small drone, which was the real reason that the cranes kept flying up and down. I photographed the man, his white SUV, and his license plate and would like to report him for wildlife harassment.  I originally estimated 2000 cranes but have decided it's probably double that amount based on the second huge concentration that was in the playa east of the lake.

Media notes: A continuing, juvenile Sandhill Crane photographed by Curtis A. Marantz on 27 October 2021 in the park east of the community center at Lake Tamarisk, Desert Center, Riverside County, California.
Observation Details: Wurster spotted the continuing crane walking around on the open lawns in the park east of Parkview Drive, where it remained for the entire time that we had it under observation.  Typical of young cranes that I have seen, this bird was rather tame, allowing a close approach without ever appearing wary.  After taking some photos and studying this bird carefully, we continued along our route leaving it near where we had found it, and where it had been present for several days.  I never heard this bird vocalize, and we never saw it fly, or even to spread its wings. This was a large wading bird that appeared superficially like a Great Blue Heron, yet with obvious structural and plumage differences to go along with the fact that it was waling around an open, grassy field.  The bill tapered from a base of medium depth to a pointed tip along a culmen that appeared to be perfectly straight, and with the lower edge of the lower mandible equally straight.  Moreover, this bird’s bill was shorter than that of a heron, in that it was only very slightly longer than the head was wide.  Complementing the short bill was a forehead that was sloping, yet notably steeper than that of a heron, and merging with a rounded crown, all on a head that had more mass than that of a heron.  The neck was long and relatively slim, though stouter where it met the body than where it met the small head.  I also did not notice an obvious S-curve to the neck, though I also never saw this bird in flight to see if it retracted its neck.  The body was plump, full-chested, and with a posture that was midway between horizontal and diagonal, and with a hunch-backed appearance.  The rear part of the bird represented a “bustle” that reflected large tertials that curved over the tips of the wings and tail, and given that I never saw the wings spread, I was unable to see either the primary projection or the placement of the wingtips relative to a tail that I likewise never saw clearly.  The legs were long and seemingly stouter than those of a heron, but I failed to notice much detail on the feet. Although this bird was grayish in part, its patterns and coloration were unlike those of a heron.  The forehead, from the base of the upper mandible up to its junction with the crown, was a light gray color that lacked brown or reddish tones, but which extended through the face and the superciliary region.  Contrasting sharply with the gray forehead and supercilium, the crown was a bright cinnamon in color back to the nape, and to a lesser degree down the back of the neck.  Although the face was generally a light to medium-gray in color, this gray blended to whitish on the throat, and the gray also contrasted with a rounded spot of cinnamon on the auriculars that was completely encircled by gray that extended back through the superciliary region before curving down around their rear terminus along the sides of the neck.  I think the foreneck was more grayish than buff, but I am now a little unsure about this, and I am likewise unsure about the precise color of the underparts, which I thought were more brownish than gray, though I cannot now be certain.  The back of the neck was a cinnamon-buff where it met a back of similar coloration, and I further noted narrow, but seemingly well-defined, shaft-streaks that were dusky, if not blackish.  The scapulars had a bold pattern that combined wedge-shaped centers that were slate gray, and with some feather seemingly having even darker lines along the shaft, with bright, cinnamon-rufous edges on both sides to create a bold pattern.  I am not sure I never clearly saw the lesser coverts, but several pairs of what I thought were median coverts visible on the closed wing had a pattern that combined a medium-gray base with a bright, cinnamon-rufous tip and a narrow, but well-defined, stripe of slate-gray that ran along the shaft.  I thought at least some of the greater coverts had a similar pattern, but I had a harder time seeing this.  The enlarged tertials combined both gray and rufous, but I was unsure about the precise pattern on these feathers, and I am not sure I ever clearly saw the remaining remiges, rump, or rectrices. The bill appeared mostly slate-gray at times, but more pinkish in others, but close inspection seemed to suggest that the upper mandible was slate-gray apart from a pinkish cast to the cutting edge, but that the lower mandible was mostly a dull, dusky pink in color.  The irides appeared to be an odd shade of olive-brown, and surrounding the eye was a narrow orbital-ring that was yellow in color.  Finally, the legs and toes were slate-gray in color, but I managed to overlook the precise color of the claws, though I thought they were dark.

*Very rare in NYC, and even more so in this context (foraging on the beach). Per local beachgoer the bird was here yesterday, and it comes after a similar looking bird was photographed on Dyker Beach Golf Course on 7/15. Locality: Willcox--Lake Cochise and Twin Lakes Golf Course
Observation Details: When we saw so many flying up then landing again, we hurried over from the golf course to Cochise Lake. When we arrived, there was a girl that was trying to walk out into the flock and scaring them. I yelled at her three times before she went back to her car. At the car, what may have been her father, was operating a small drone, which was the real reason that the cranes kept flying up and down. I photographed the man, his white SUV, and his license plate and would like to report him for wildlife harassment.  I originally estimated 2000 cranes but have decided it's probably double that amount based on the second huge concentration that was in the playa east of the lake.

Two were calling from a distance.  One was walking on the prairie just south of Pond 2.  One was sitting on the nest at Teal Pond.  Luckily I saw it stand up which revealed two eggs that it had been sitting on.  It bent over and turned the eggs and then sat down on the eggs again to continue the incubation.  I saw the pair of Sandhill Cranes first build the nest on 4 Mar 2024.  They seldom visited the nest after that.  The rain that fell after that date cause the level of the water in Teal Pond to rise considerably.  I thought the cranes would not nest there again because of the high water and wet nest.  I was wrong.  They added a few more cattail leaves and raised the nest a bit higher above the water and now have laid eggs.  In the past two years when they have nest there and laid eggs there the eggs have been predated and destroyed.  Will it happen again this year.  Time will tell.

Wurster spotted the continuing crane walking around on the open lawns in the park east of Parkview Drive, where it remained for the entire time that we had it under observation.  Typical of young cranes that I have seen, this bird was rather tame, allowing a close approach without ever appearing wary.  After taking some photos and studying this bird carefully, we continued along our route leaving it near where we had found it, and where it had been present for several days.  I never heard this bird vocalize, and we never saw it fly, or even to spread its wings. This was a large wading bird that appeared superficially like a Great Blue Heron, yet with obvious structural and plumage differences to go along with the fact that it was waling around an open, grassy field.  The bill tapered from a base of medium depth to a pointed tip along a culmen that appeared to be perfectly straight, and with the lower edge of the lower mandible equally straight.  Moreover, this bird’s bill was shorter than that of a heron, in that it was only very slightly longer than the head was wide.  Complementing the short bill was a forehead that was sloping, yet notably steeper than that of a heron, and merging with a rounded crown, all on a head that had more mass than that of a heron.  The neck was long and relatively slim, though stouter where it met the body than where it met the small head.  I also did not notice an obvious S-curve to the neck, though I also never saw this bird in flight to see if it retracted its neck.  The body was plump, full-chested, and with a posture that was midway between horizontal and diagonal, and with a hunch-backed appearance.  The rear part of the bird represented a “bustle” that reflected large tertials that curved over the tips of the wings and tail, and given that I never saw the wings spread, I was unable to see either the primary projection or the placement of the wingtips relative to a tail that I likewise never saw clearly.  The legs were long and seemingly stouter than those of a heron, but I failed to notice much detail on the feet. Although this bird was grayish in part, its patterns and coloration were unlike those of a heron.  The forehead, from the base of the upper mandible up to its junction with the crown, was a light gray color that lacked brown or reddish tones, but which extended through the face and the superciliary region.  Contrasting sharply with the gray forehead and supercilium, the crown was a bright cinnamon in color back to the nape, and to a lesser degree down the back of the neck.  Although the face was generally a light to medium-gray in color, this gray blended to whitish on the throat, and the gray also contrasted with a rounded spot of cinnamon on the auriculars that was completely encircled by gray that extended back through the superciliary region before curving down around their rear terminus along the sides of the neck.  I think the foreneck was more grayish than buff, but I am now a little unsure about this, and I am likewise unsure about the precise color of the underparts, which I thought were more brownish than gray, though I cannot now be certain.  The back of the neck was a cinnamon-buff where it met a back of similar coloration, and I further noted narrow, but seemingly well-defined, shaft-streaks that were dusky, if not blackish.  The scapulars had a bold pattern that combined wedge-shaped centers that were slate gray, and with some feather seemingly having even darker lines along the shaft, with bright, cinnamon-rufous edges on both sides to create a bold pattern.  I am not sure I never clearly saw the lesser coverts, but several pairs of what I thought were median coverts visible on the closed wing had a pattern that combined a medium-gray base with a bright, cinnamon-rufous tip and a narrow, but well-defined, stripe of slate-gray that ran along the shaft.  I thought at least some of the greater coverts had a similar pattern, but I had a harder time seeing this.  The enlarged tertials combined both gray and rufous, but I was unsure about the precise pattern on these feathers, and I am not sure I ever clearly saw the remaining remiges, rump, or rectrices. The bill appeared mostly slate-gray at times, but more pinkish in others, but close inspection seemed to suggest that the upper mandible was slate-gray apart from a pinkish cast to the cutting edge, but that the lower mandible was mostly a dull, dusky pink in color.  The irides appeared to be an odd shade of olive-brown, and surrounding the eye was a narrow orbital-ring that was yellow in color.  Finally, the legs and toes were slate-gray in color, but I managed to overlook the precise color of the claws, though I thought they were dark.

Media notes: Image taken with a super zoom lens. Seen here ia a family of 3, resident, Florida Sandhill Cranes; lakeside, very nearby their nest-site #3, this nest material seen at the bottom edge of this photo. Three nest-sites have been used in 2021 and 2 used during the last 30 days; these 2 (not the "original" nest-site; the orig. nest-site used by this mating couple in prior years and for 2 weeks beyond their 2-chick hatchings this year on Feb. 28, and March 1 2021)... two additional nest were constructed by these adults in the last 3 weeks; predator issues. Shown in this photo are the adult male, the adult female and 1 remaining colt aged approx. 37 days. A family of 3, now, after a Bald Eagle took colt 1 (of 2) a fews days ago.

Locality: Side Road 10, Meldrum Bay, Ontario, CA (45.937, -83.318)

Observation Details: Super friggin weird. I was preparing lunch and looked out the window when I saw a Sandhill Crane at close range slowly striding through my backyard. It walked slowly but steadily uphill and across the street to a neighbor’s yard where I was able to get photos from my front porch. It walked in front of their house then up their driveway between cars and behind their house, continuing steadily up the hill through the neighborhood. It was panting heavily in the heat and giving quiet croaks. Maybe the same bird that was hanging out at Arby’s in Marietta back on August 1st?  I also had a lost midsummer crane in Bartow Co. 2 years ago (Taff Rd., July 26, 2017).   We get plenty of flyovers during migration, but never expected it as an actual “yard” bird, much less in mid August!

Media notes: One sandhill crane flew in, joining the other at dusk. They then began duetting. The vocalizing was a lot more animated and fast-paced at the start (I missed this part in the display). They ended with these final few duets. Likely male and female because this is a duet, but cannot tell by plumage. Contributed for the female bird song project: www.femalebirdsong.org

Media notes: Part of a much longer recording recorded with my parabolic mic on a tripod pointed north towards the cranes from the path. I did not adjust the levels between the clips at all. I arbitrarily chose minute intervals that were ten minutes apart; The first clip was recorded at 6:37am, second at 6:47am, and third at 6:57am. By the third clip, the volume of the cranes had diminished slightly and you can pick out individuals more whereas the volume and number of cranes vocalizing in the first two create a thick wall of sound. Quite Spectacular. The audio file of combined clips normalized to -3db.

This large gray bird had a long neck that was extended during flight and long grayish legs that extend beyond the tail.  The flight feathers had darker edges noticed during flight and some birds had rusty patches on their wings.  An adult has a red patch of skin from the mid-crown to the base of bill, which is brown on immature birds.  The bill is long, dagger-like and grayish.  The voice is a bugled “kukuku-roo”. These birds were spread out over dozens of acres of a harvested corn field that had a few wet depressions. The somewhat similar great blue heron is mostly gray, has a whitish head with black lateral crown stripes and short black plumes.  The large heavy bill is yellowish orange and the long neck is coiled during flight.  The voice is a raspy “kraaar”.

On ground amount. It is apparent they have all migrated but for a few. Only two groups seen in the entire area where just 15 days ago there were over 7,000. Up to 17,000 the week before that.  Two groups were seen south of 1125E with none seen near the larger open marsh pond east of 600E.  Later, around 230 PM CST, it appeared that the majority of cranes had moved to the pond area as they were near the edges.  Only seven cranes seen in flight while I was in the area.

Locality: Aransas Bay--Rockport/Fulton to Aransas NWR by boat

Observation Details: All seen on the ground in the survey area with most (4700) on the east side of 600E near the marsh/pond and ditch.  Large flocks previously seen to the south were seen heading to this resting/roosting area. Hardly any (400) seen on the north side of 1000S today and none on the east side of 500E or out in the open in the ag land north and south of 1100S.  This weeks worth of highly documented surveys should convince you that the filter needs to be changed for LaPorte Co, as has repeatedly been suggested at the bottom of the last paragragh; Change the filter to 20,000 as it is for Starke Co, which is less than two (2) miles to the south. Jackson and Green Counties also have 20,000 as the filter cutoff. , and Starke County. LaPorte County is an adjacent county to Jasper-Pulaski and the SACR are only going to continue increasing.   Although this count of 7,360 is just an on-ground count with no dusk flight count the SACR on ground numbers dropped in the past two daily readings from the on-ground high of 13,900 on 11.29.17 and also from 12,480 on 12.04.17, just four (4) days ago. Excluding the first count the mean on-ground count from 11.29.17 through 12.06.17 was 11,081. The drop in the on-ground count is associated with the drop in the temperature, as would be expected. The temperature dropped down to 13.5 F at 0515 at the LaPorte Municipal Airport, and down to 12.6 F at Kingsford Heights  this AM. Although in speaking with the man that plows the local roads some do remain around during the winter as he stated that they would be out in the road when he was plowing.   Surveyed this area intensively for @ one week. Had 10,400 on 11.26.17; 14,900 on 11.29; and 17,350 on 12.01; 15,605 on 12.02.17; 16,803 on 12.03.17; 17,080 on 12.04.17, 11,100 on 12.06.17; and 7,360 on 12.08.17 ( which did not include the dusk flight count.). Fairly consistent counts until the cold weather hit.  Believe numbers dropped the last two days due to the colder weather causing migration.  17,000 previously reported for LaPorte Co in March of 2015 http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S22388042 without any supporting documentation   and the SACR population is experiencing an increase. Not this many were here two (2) years ago. Many other local checklists by several observers from earlier this year showing 5,000-8,000 SACR @ 5 miles to the SW of this roosting location. It is 23 miles to Jasper-Pulaski.  This observation was continued until dusk to include the SACR flying in to roost as observer had knowledge and experience of seeing large flocks nearby earlier this year. There are no other dusk checklists that have been done at this location. This roost is a northern roost that the cranes foraging nearby use rather than flying the 23 miles to Jasper -Pulaski.  Same as gulls use local lakes as roosting locations rather than returning to Lake Michigan after foraging at landfills. One checklist done earlier this year, by this observer, noted that 5,000 cranes were heading to the 600E area. http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S34610409  Another checklist which the observer did found 3,000 SACR flying in a southerly direction to the north of the checklist location  http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S27937963. There are many cranes here.  Three (3) individuals that the observer sppoke with during the week noted they thought there were more cranes here than at Jasper-Pulaski. If you look at a map the area available to them is larger at this location. Recommend changing the filter to 20,000 as it is for Jackson and Green Counties. LaPorte County is an adjacent county to Jasper-Pulaski and the SACR are only going to continue increasing.

Media notes: Immature in the center.
Observation Details: 12.18.17 Change the filter to 20,000 as it is for Starke Co, which is less than two (2) miles to the south. Jackson and Green Counties also have 20,000 as the filter cutoff. , and Starke County. LaPorte County is an adjacent county to Jasper-Pulaski and the SACR are only going to continue increasing.   12.14.17  Still no action on this checklist or these http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S40832917   and http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S40852067.  10700 previously approved for a 11.26.17 checklist at this same location.  17000 previously approved at location @ eight (8) miles to the SW in 2015  http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S22388042 with no supporting documentation and SACR numbers are increasing.  Filter should be set to 20,000 as in Jackson and Greene Counties.  Surveyed this area intensively for @ one week. Had 10,400 on 11.26.17; 14,900 on 11.29; and 17,350 on 12.01; 15,605 on 12.02.17; 16,803 on 12.03.17; 17,080 on 12.04.17, 11,100 on 12.06.17; and 7,360 on 12.08.17 ( which did not include the dusk flight count.). Fairly consistent counts until the cold weather hit.  Believe numbers dropped the last two days due to the colder weather causing migration.    FHC Counted cranes on the ground and those coming from @ 417 PM - 450 PM.   10,980 on the ground  + 6,370 in flight = 17,350 cranes  S 600E in field on east side south of pond- 2600 birds @ 1440 PM Upon looking these did not take flight en masse to move to the roosting area immediately to the north before 445 PM. The area they were thickest in was immediately to the south of it.  There were an additional 700 birds seen on the east side of S 600E, north of the east pond at 445 PM however.  E 1125S, east of S 600E  -  1060 birds @ 1510 PM 1030 on the south side and 30 on the north Didn't check it at dusk.  E 1100N, west of S 600E, near the low spot - 1320 birds @ 1535 PM Not as many as there were two (2) days ago.  E 1000S, north side, west of S 550E - 5,000 birds @ 1600 PM There were none on the east half of this field as there had been two (2) days ago. These were counted by scope and many were missed due to some being out of sight in low spots and behind vegetation from the best viewing location. Since only about half of the surface area previously covered by the birds two days ago was now covered that estimate of 7,000 birds was most likely low.  This flock took off all at the same time while I was there starting with the birds at the far west end and flew across the road and settled on the east side of S 500E which was the typical staging area that I recall from the past. None settled in the marsh on the south side of E 1000S, but all settled on the ag land on the west side of it.  S 500E, east side, south of E 1000S - 1000 birds @ 1550 PM  S 550E, east side low spot - zero (0) birds at 215 PM CST and didn't see any there just after dusk. Some were seen settling there at @ 445 PM CST but it was too dark to count. These birds were coming from the north.  Birds Flying in from 1615 PM to 1650 PM  - 6,370 birds 4,070 + 2300  Sat on S 500E and counted birds periodically, about every three minutes, as they came in. From 417 PM to 434 PM I had a total of 2,440 birds in 6 counts spaced 3 minutes apart. Birds seen in flight were 300, 600, 220, 600, 190, and 530. Averaging the total birds by the six counts gives 407 birds per minute. Multiplying this rate by the time watched of 20 minutes gives total birds of 8,140. To get amount to use I divided that amount in half, giving 4,070 cranes, which would subtract any of the birds previously seen on the ground to the south (1,060 + 1,320 = 2,380 birds) plus an additional 1,690 birds to avoid overcounting.  More birds continued to come in after 437 PM until the time I left, with more coming in yet. Had @ 125 birds minute by averaging. Time would be 23 minutes from 437-500PM and used 100 birds per min for 2300 birds. Cranes were still coming in from the north when I left.

Since only about half of the surface area previously covered by the birds two days ago was now covered that estimate of 7,000 birds was most likely low.  This flock took off all at the same time while I was there starting with the birds at the far west end and flew across the road and settled on the east side of S 500E which was the typical staging area that I recall from the past. None settled in the marsh on the south side of E 1000S, but all settled on the ag land on the west side of it.  S 500E, east side, south of E 1000S - 1000 birds @ 1550 PM  S 550E, east side low spot - zero (0) birds at 215 PM CST and didn't see any there just after dusk. Some were seen settling there at @ 445 PM CST but it was too dark to count. These birds were coming from the north.  Birds Flying in from 1615 PM to 1650 PM  - 6,370 birds 4,070 + 2300  Sat on S 500E and counted birds periodically, about every three minutes, as they came in. From 417 PM to 434 PM I had a total of 2,440 birds in 6 counts spaced 3 minutes apart. Birds seen in flight were 300, 600, 220, 600, 190, and 530. Averaging the total birds by the six counts gives 407 birds per minute. Multiplying this rate by the time watched of 20 minutes gives total birds of 8,140. To get amount to use I divided that amount in half, giving 4,070 cranes, which would subtract any of the birds previously seen on the ground to the south (1,060 + 1,320 = 2,380 birds) plus an additional 1,690 birds to avoid overcounting.  More birds continued to come in after 437 PM until the time I left, with more coming in yet. Had @ 125 birds minute by averaging. Time would be 23 minutes from 437-500PM and used 100 birds per min for 2300 birds. Cranes were still coming in from the north when I left.
Doing laps around Cape Island; subspecies ID by large size, long bills, long leg projection past tail.

Locality: Cemetary Rd at W Willow St
Observation Details: My Aunt spotted something on two legs in the sage brush near Cemetery Rd. It turned out to be a Sandhill Crane! It was super close to the road! It then walked across the road and walked through the field. Then suddenly another one popped up in the field right in front of us! We were snapping pictures of him and were not noticing the other crane had a chick, until mother and chick had gotten some distance away! We than noticed the cute chick and got okay pics of it. But then the funniest thing ever happened! A red winged blackbird pair decided to chase the male crane off their  territory! The male red wing jumped on the cranes tail feathers, and rode him as he would a horse! I got an okay video of it! Ebird won't let me post my video, but I have a snip of it posted at the red winged blackbird.

Media notes: Two sandhill cranes checking out a large soft-shelled turtle.
Observation Details: Two cranes were following a soft-shelled turtle that was climbing up the hill from the lake.  The turtle was undoubtedly looking for a place to lay her eggs. (Otherwise, I never see them here.)  One crane made as if to peck at the turtle, but when the turtle moved, the crane jumped back.  I don't know whether the cranes were fully adult, although they were large enough to be.  I don't often see cranes in my yard and never with young ones.  I think the ones that wander around like that may be last year''s young that are looking for a territory of their own.

Observation Details: Mississippi subspecies.  One bird had  2 bands (orange over blue) on left leg and long band with transmitter on right leg. All birds were seen on Briarcrest Drive near Gautier, MS.

Evidently a pair (?), continuing in the area. They flew in over the road from the north and landed by the small pond at 371 Kiddsville Rd. Watched them for about an hour from across the road. Homeowner came out and planted cabbages in a garden where they had been standing. They moved away, and he ignored them. One chased after a redwing blackbird which had been diving at them. They got rained on for a while, and after it stopped for a bit they began a "dancing" display, several times. I know they aren't supposed to breed here, but maybe they don't know that. ;) Presumably they start this display before they reach breeding areas? I got video of this twice but file type doesn't load here. Very exciting lifer!

Locality: Willcox--Lake Cochise and Twin Lakes Golf Course
Observation Details: When we saw so many flying up then landing again, we hurried over from the golf course to Cochise Lake. When we arrived, there was a girl that was trying to walk out into the flock and scaring them. I yelled at her three times before she went back to her car. At the car, what may have been her father, was operating a small drone, which was the real reason that the cranes kept flying up and down. I photographed the man, his white SUV, and his license plate and would like to report him for wildlife harassment.  I originally estimated 2000 cranes but have decided it's probably double that amount based on the second huge concentration that was in the playa east of the lake.

400 in the corn, 200 on the hay field. The rest flew in and around. The southeast pond accepted hundreds of the cranes. A very late fly in as they just kept coming in. Normally they are done for the day sooner.

Locality: 出水市--出水市ツル観察��ンター (Izumi--Izumi Crane Observation Center)
Salton Sea NWR--Unit 1 (no public access north of observation deck)
Uxbridge Community Gardens and Soccer Fields
Observation Details: Was standing in the garden area when four large birds came flying in low right at me - to my surprise, Sandhill Cranes.  Flew in close right over my head; I realized they were heading for the soccer fields behind me.  Sure enough they landed there.  They did not stay long.  One other birder got to see, then we checked on later and could not relocate.  Maybe they were hiding somewhere in the weedy fields; we didn't see them leave, so don't know.
